/////////////////////
FORMATTING STRINGS
/////////////////////

- We can format a string by adding substring/s within it.
- The "format()" funtion allow us to format strings

/////////////////////
PLACEHOLDERS { }
/////////////////////

- It help us control which part of the string should be formatted.
- in this example, we will concatenate or add a substring to where the {} are placed

x = 'I love {} very much!'
text = x.format("myself")

print(text)

///////////////////////////
MULTILPLE PLACEHOLDERS
///////////////////////////

x = "I love {}, {}, and {} very much!"
text = x.format('Python', 'HTML', 'CSS')

print(text)

_______________
USING INDEXES
_______________

- We can use index numbers to specify exactly where the values should be placed

x = "I love {2}, {1}, and {0} very much!"
text = x.format('Python', 'HTML', 'CSS')

_____________________
USING NAME INDEXES
_____________________

- We can also used named indexes to specify exactly where the values should be placed.
- The arguments of the 'format( )' function should be in key/value pairs "key = value"

x = The title of this song is {favesong} by {artist} and the genre is {genre}."

text = x.format(favesong = 'Sometimes i see colors too', artist = 'Just Neighbors', genre = 'Math Rock / Midwest Emo')
print(text)

